{{Infobox rally |name = 2019 Monte Carlo Rally |native_name = 87<sup>e</sup> Rallye Automobile Monte-Carlo |round = 1 |season_no = 14 |championship = [[2019 World Rally Championship]] |previous_round = |next_round = 2019 Rally Sweden |country = {{MCO}} / {{FRA}} |image = |caption = |start = [[Monte Carlo Casino|Casino Square]], [[Monaco]] |finish = Casino Square, Monaco |rallybase = {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Gap, Hautes-Alpes|Gap]], [[Hautes-Alpes]] |startdate = 24 |enddate = 27 January 2019 |stages = 16 |stagekm = 322.81 |transportkm = |overallkm = |surface = Tarmac and snow |driver1 = |codriver1 = |team1 = |time1 = |driver2 = |codriver2 = |team2 = |time2 = |powerstage_driver = |powerstage_codriver = |powerstage_team = |crewsreg = |teamsstart = |teamsfinish = }}
The '''2019 Monte Carlo Rally''' (formally known as the '''87<sup>e</sup> Rallye Automobile Monte-Carlo''') is a [[motorsport|motor racing]] event for [[rallying|rally cars]] that will be held over four days between 25 and 28 January 2018.<ref name="FIA-11">{{cite news|url=https://www.fia.com/news/fia-announces-world-motor-sport-council-decisions-11|title=FIA announces World Motor Sport Council decisions|work=fia.com|publisher=[[Fédération Internationale de l'Automobile]]|date=12 October 2018|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref> It marks the eighty-seventh running of the [[Monte Carlo Rally]], and is the first round of the [[2019 World Rally Championship]] and its support category, the [[2019 World Rally Championship-2|WRC-2]]. The 2019 event is based in the town of [[Gap, Hautes-Alpes|Gap]] in the [[Hautes-Alpes]] department of France and contests sixteen [[Special stage (rallying)|special stages]]. The rally covers a total competitive distance of {{convert|322.81|km|mi|2|abbr=on}}.<ref name="rmc 2019">{{cite web|url=http://acm.mc/en/edition/rallye-monte-carlo-edition-2019|title=Rallye Monte-Carlo – Edition 2019|work=acm.mc|publisher=[[Automobile Club de Monaco]]|accessdate=19 October 2018}}</ref>
Reigning World Drivers' and World Co-Drivers Champions [[Sébastien Ogier]] and [[Julien Ingrassia]] are the defending rally winners. Their 2018 former team, [[M-Sport World Rally Team|M-Sport Ford WRT]], are the defending manufacturers' winners.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.speedcafe.com/2018/01/29/ogier-wins-rallye-monte-carlo/|title=Ogier wins Rallye Monte-Carlo|work=[[Speedcafe|speedcafe.com]]|date=29 January 2018|accessdate=29 January 2018}}</ref> The [[Škoda Motorsport]] crew of [[Jan Kopecký]] and [[Pavel Dresler]] are the World Rally Championship-2 defending rally winners.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wrc.com/en/wrc/news/january-2018/sunday-wrc-2-wrap/page/5176--12-12-.html|title=Sunday in WRC 2: Kopecký Wins in Style|work=wrc.com|publisher=[[WRC Promoter GmbH]]|date=28 January 2018|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref>
